First thing, we need to download the target area of interest form NEON. We will use the NEON utilities package and specifically the byTileAOP function to retrieve the tile of interest. We will be downloading 2 tiles: (1) the RGB orthophoto, the dpID being DP1.30010.001, used for detecting trees (2) the CHM, the dpID being DP3.30015.001, used for estimating the size of each predicted tree

We will be using OSBS data, year 2021. For this utorial, the Easting and Northign will be 402000 and 3286000

Now, lets try to get crow predictions, shall we! The methods we are using today are based on generating polygons from the canopy height model. If we have time we will see how to do it by using state of teh art deep learning and RGB data. Because it may be too advanced, however, it will not be todays standard approach Maybe next year!

Because of time and internet limitaiton, we will be using the CHM directly for tree detection. Ideally wed like to use either (1) LiDAR data, or (2) deep learning applications from RGB data. Well see later how to eventually use a deep learning application for tree detection on NEON data.

Next, lets extract the height for each individual tree

## Joining, by = "individual"

lets plot CHM density. what is the variation within the tile?

lets check, how does it vary with elevation? lets download the elevation data from NEON

byTileAOP(dpID = "DP3.30024.001", site = "OSBS", year = 2021, easting = 402000, 
          check.size = F, northing = 3286000, savepath = img_pt)

dem_path = list.files("indir/DP3.30024.001/", pattern = "_DTM.tif", recursive = T, full.names = T)
dem = raster::raster(dem_path)

Unfortunately the traditional extract function can be quite slow, as you noticed when extracting the CHM. To reduce the time required to extract information, lets turn our polygons into points, getting the centroid for each individual tree

tree_stems_points = sf::st_centroid(boxes_with_height) 
## Warning in st_centroid.sf(boxes_with_height): st_centroid assumes attributes are
## constant over geometries of x
elevation_at_tree_stems_points=raster::extract(dem, tree_stems_points)

tree_stems_points["elevation"] = elevation_at_tree_stems_points

grd = sf::st_as_sf(sf::st_make_grid(tree_stems_points, cellsize = 100, square = F))
grd$plt = 1:nrow(grd)
tree_stems_points = sf::st_join(tree_stems_points, grd)

plot(tree_stems_points["plt"])

tree_stems_points %>% dplyr::filter(plt ==37) %>% dplyr::select(plt) %>% plot(col = sf.colors(12, categorical = TRUE))
## Warning in plot.sf(., col = sf.colors(12, categorical = TRUE)): col is not of
## length 1 or nrow(x): colors will be recycled; use pal to specify a color palette

#assign trees at the border between two plots to a single plot ID
tree_stems_points = tree_stems_points %>% dplyr::group_by(individual) %>% dplyr::slice(1)

However, we have now points, what if we want to append this information to the boxes? We can join by individual ID!

tree_stems_points_df = data.frame(tree_stems_points) %>%
  dplyr::select(-one_of("geometry"))
boxes_with_height_and_elevation = dplyr::left_join(boxes_with_height,tree_stems_points_df )
## Joining, by = c("individual", "Height", "crown_area")

Or more simply join by spatial feature. This should work in this case because the method used doesnt allow two crowns to be overlapped. However, it may not be the case for results from cases where crowns overlap and a tree stem may be falling within the boundaries of multiple crowns. For this reason we would suggest to join by identifier, as suggested above


boxes_with_height_and_elevation_by_spatial = sf::st_join(boxes_with_height, tree_stems_points )

Now, we got trees, their size, their elevation but we dont have yet the measure of their diversity! Thats when the grid plotting comes handy!

Lets get a simple quantification of variation: the gini index

boxes_with_height_and_elevation = data.frame(boxes_with_height_and_elevation) 
hmin = min(boxes_with_height_and_elevation$Height)
hmax = max(boxes_with_height_and_elevation$Height)
custom_bins = seq(hmin,hmax, by=5)
boxes_with_height_and_elevation = boxes_with_height_and_elevation %>%
  mutate(h_class = cut(Height, breaks = custom_bins))
#boxes_with_height_and_elevation$h_class = findInterval((boxes_with_height_and_elevation$Height), seq(from = 2, to = 40, by = 1))

h_div = boxes_with_height_and_elevation %>%
  dplyr::group_by(plt) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(n_trees_per_plot = n())
h_div = h_div %>% ungroup %>% 
  dplyr::group_by(h_class, plt) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(hclass_n = n())

h_div = h_div %>% ungroup %>% 
  dplyr::group_by(plt, h_class) %>% 
  dplyr::slice(1)
h_div = h_div %>% dplyr::group_by(plt)  %>%
  dplyr::summarize(gini_numerator = sum(hclass_n *(hclass_n -1)), 
            gini_denominator = unique(n_trees_per_plot)*(unique(n_trees_per_plot)-1),
            plot_elevation = mean(elevation),
            plot_max_height = max(Height))

h_div$GINI = 1- h_div$gini_numerator/h_div$gini_denominator

Now we have all the information we need! So, lets finally check whether elevation affect size diversity in a transect from sandhill pine fores to wetland!

ggplot(h_div, aes(x = plot_elevation, y = GINI)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + theme_bw()
